text: The Science Fiction Radio Show A commentary on science fiction today Presented by the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association This is David Cruz Daryl Lane And David Carson This show will be an interview with science fiction author Joan D. Vingy Joan Vingy is one of the best of the group of young science fiction authors that appeared in the 70s Her first story, Tin Soldier, was published in 1974 And since then she's written two novels and a number of novellas and short stories In 1977 she received a Hugo Award for one of her stories, Eyes of Amber She has experimented convincingly with a future history and with world building And is noted for her credible and fascinating aliens Perhaps most readers though respond most strongly to her characters They are vividly and realistically drawn, easily identified with And they remain with the reader long after he's finished one of her stories How did you get started writing science fiction? Well, there are sort of two versions of that in a way There's my official writing career Which began after I first got married to Werner Vingy, my now ex-husband He was a science fiction writer at the time And I had been a person who fooled around with writing for a while before that I would just diddle around with it I used to want to be an artist and writing was just something I did kind of privately And never showed to anybody and rarely finished anything either But Werner encouraged me to take it seriously if I was going to write By that time I'd abandoned wanting to be an artist Because my college art professors had ruined my desire to do art And I was sort of casting about And he knew that I liked to write And so he encouraged me to attempt to take it seriously And sit down and do something and finish it And so I decided that I would take him up on that And I started doing a story Which turned out to be the first story that I sold It was called Tin Soldier And when I started writing it I didn't know if I'd ever get it finished or anything But I did get it finished And I showed it to him And he said he thought it was saleable And so I started sending it out And I did sell it And after that I was hooked of course And I wanted to go on being a writer Does your background in anthropology have much influence on your writing? Well actually it does play a pretty big role in the writing Because I find that anthropology and science fiction Have a lot of things in common for me Archaeology was my specialty And archaeology is the anthropology of the past And science fiction for me is the anthropology of the future They form sort of a long continuum And the thing I like about both science fiction and anthropology Is that they allow you to see how other people do things And that other people's lives are not led the same way yours is And that there are other ways of coping That aren't necessarily the ones you've always known That other people do things differently And get along perfectly well that way I love the way that both anthropology and science fiction Can take your preconceptions and kind of turn them around 180 degrees And make you say gee I never thought of it like that before Specifically I like to use my anthropological background too When I'm setting up societies for the stories that I'm going to write I do sort of an ethnography which is a cultural study Only I have to make up details of the culture in general Instead of just studying an anthropological culture I do get a lot of details, bits and pieces of interesting societies Which I recombine sometimes to create science fictional societies It gives you a way of thinking I think that's very useful when you're writing a science fiction story Looking for different ways Hoping that when you send your rocket ship out into the galaxy It's not going to come to a planet where everyone acts like 1950s Earth And I really enjoy exploring differences in societies And things like that And well mythology is kind of an offshoot of anthropology That I find is very useful to science fiction too I get a lot of story ideas from mythology And a lot of, I think, just kind of underlying strengths That are almost like fantasy And I like to weave them into the science fiction Which is what I most like to write And I think it gives a stronger appeal somehow Could that be because we have sort of a common background of folktales and myths And by weaving these into your stories You sort of reinforce or update some of the old basic stories That our culture is based on Right, yeah, I think very much so I think there really are certain universalities in myths too Which kind of strike everybody At a very deep and basic level And if you could capture some of that same feeling In a story when you write it Maybe by employing elements consciously or unconsciously Of, you know, out of the mythology I think that you could really have a very deep emotional impact on the reader Which I think is probably what every writer would like to do I've noticed that a lot of your stories seem to have a happy ending Could that be because some of them have their basis in folktales Or is it because you're just basically an optimistic person? I think it's more that I'm basically an optimistic person Actually, not every single one of my stories is based on a folktale A lot of them do have those elements in them But some don't It's just that I really, I hate to leave a story feeling totally depressed by it And so I think I hate to write a story that's totally depressing Frequently, I think the stories have sort of bittersweet endings Or, you know, people don't walk off hand in hand into the sunset They're usually dragging along, you know, a few suitcases full of problems too But, you know, I think the way life is, it's unrealistic usually to write a totally happy ending But I do like to have an optimistic ending When I read things, I relate to them on a very personal level I get very involved in a story And if it's a story, the end result of which is to make me feel totally depressed And feel like, you know, why bother to live? I really don't like being left feeling that way And I think I don't like feeling that way when I write, too Yes, it seems that you get very involved with your characters that you create Is it because you flesh them out so well when you create them? Or is it because the characters are sort of variations on yourself? Well, I think probably some of both I think a lot of my favorite characters are, you know, bits and pieces of me I don't know that any one of them is all me I think all people have different aspects of their personality Which come to the fore at different times Just in their day-to-day life And I think when you're writing, you can't help but Inject those personalities into characters I really do like characters in stories I like to read about characters who seem real And so I like to try and make my own characters as real as possible when I write them And I think, you know, by getting inside their heads I invariably, you know, stick a few of my thoughts in there I do have some characters who are based on other people I know And things like that, too But I do like to I like to, you know, well, when I write about strange things And new ideas in different societies I like to put people who are recognizably human Even if they're aliens, I suppose But people that the reader can relate to into those situations And let the reader see how the human being reacts To the strange set of circumstances It's not simply the strange set of circumstances which interests me Although that's, I think, why I write science fiction Because I like... I don't like to write about the same old day-to-day thing I like to explore new ground But I like to do it with actual characters Who, you know, come as close as possible To seeming like real people I like to see what they do in the given circumstances Yes Science fiction is the only literature Which allows you to explore the future Which opens up quite a few vistas That mainstream literature just doesn't have Right And that's really what I like about science fiction I read my first science fiction book When I was in ninth grade And I just felt like, you know Boy, where has this been all my life I was just swept away by it And I felt like I really hardly wanted to read anything But science fiction after that It was just so exciting to me To know these new worlds opened up to me Yes, I remember one of the characters in Eyes of Amber Is a singer, a songwriter And it seems like music plays an important role in your writing Yes, it really does, actually I seem to relate to music on a kind of subliminal level I guess it operates something like mythology for me When I hear a song I frequently get down into the song And start wondering what's going on in the background of it And, you know, the situation that's set up in the song Leads me to think, well, who are the people involved in this And how did they get here And what is this talking about? Actually, I tend to relate to songs in a very personal way That they have a kind of reality about them I frequently can't help thinking that the songwriter Must have written that about his or her own experience Even though I know it's no more likely that they did And that someone writing fiction necessarily wrote a story about their own life But I just enjoy music tremendously And it really stimulates creative juices for me So I frequently do wind up being inspired to write certain things By listening to music In fact, Eyes of Amber The title of that story is taken from the song by Buffy St. Marie Which is about someone who has a demon lover And sort of fit into the context of the story Where the alien woman thinks of the space probe as a demon And she relates to it Because it does respond to her Although she doesn't know it's the human beings on Earth She relates to it as another being And has this kind of fascination for it And it's just taking little elements like that And working them into stories It's one of the pleasures of writing for me Since you do have a rather good background in anthropology How do you go about constructing your aliens? Oh, that's an interesting question, actually I don't think I have any particular method for constructing aliens They frequently kind of arise out of other givens in the situation And out of the environment In Eyes of Amber, the aliens, although they seem superficially humanoid Were actually constructed for an entirely different nitrogen-breathing situation And they had a different situation on a world And one of the, yes, one of the noons of Saturn A world which was extremely cold And they were tryphibians Which meant that they spent part of the time in the sky Part on the land and part in the water And the creatures in Crystal Ship were sort of marsupial-like And the creatures in my story, to Belle the cat Thrived on radiation They just lived on pure radiation They lived in essentially a hot, you know, an incredibly radioactively hot swamp on a planet Hidden away in a cave But there's actually no real pattern to any of them The creatures living in the cave came out of the idea of there being Essentially natural nuclear reactors forming on the Earth There was an article somewhere about how there seemed to be the fossil remains of one somewhere in Africa, I think It seemed that at some point a concentration of ore had gotten so radioactively hot That it had actually started a thermonuclear reaction Not a bomb, but just a, you know, kind of a roiling, boiling situation And so I had these creatures that had come from a whole planet that was like that And had been shipwrecked essentially on this planet Which would be normal to human beings And they had managed to find this spot and take refuge in it And that was just, you know, it came out of trying to think of what sort of creatures would live in that environment I suppose I must in general start with the environment And then try to think about what sort of adaptations would be necessary to it I don't know, aliens are one of those things that just sort of spring out of the unconscious, I guess I don't really have a pattern for creating them Except that I start with certain givens of the culture One of the problems with creating aliens is that if you make them too alien Then the reader can't understand them or relate to them And they just seem to be essentially nonsensical It's very difficult to try to convey a feeling of alienness And yet something that a human being can still relate to And not simply say, you know, what is this junk? I don't understand this And stop reading the book A lot of science fiction writers have talked about that And there are frequently accusations about Well, you know, the aliens are not really alien enough But then you come down to the old bottom line That if they are alien enough Even if one human being can imagine something that alien Someone else may not be able to understand it So you're always caught in the mind when you're writing about aliens In To Bell the Cat, you've created one of the most alien aliens I've ever encountered The being, as I understand it, is in two parts The intelligence is located deep in a cave And it controls its mobile parts, the little creatures And all other parts of the cave and out on the surface But its thought processes are amazing How did you come up with this idea? This reminds me of a story about Robert Browning When a woman asked him one time what one of his poems meant And he said, Madam, when I wrote that Only God and I knew what it meant And now only God knows I can't actually remember how I came up with that idea It's terrible I don't know whether it's in my notes anywhere or not I think it must have grown Kind of grown out of the idea of specialization in animals Where, you know, a human being is, biologically speaking A very unspecialized creature Because it has fingernails Which are the most primitive form of things As opposed to a claw or a hoof Which are adaptations, you know, specializations of nails And, you know, there are various other things about the human body Which are, quote, primitive biologically And I guess I may have been thinking about specialization Developing to an extreme Where actual different parts of the body Became separate entities And they were all controlled by the mind Which stayed in one spot Some of the specialized parts were particularly strong And some were particularly agile And things like that And they could be sent out kind of far-ranging And controlled telepathically by the brain Which just stayed at home in safety And there were essentially two levels of organism Which made up one creature And the specialized creatures that the brain controlled Had no particular brain of their own Only sort of a rudimentary receiver So that it could send them its commands And it could receive back from various impressions Of what they were doing I wound up, the way they communicate Became, it was sort of like writing poetry For me, I used to like to write poetry And this became as close to a million as I had For a long time And then while the brain creatures Were communicating with each other With the other brains And discussing their plight They were at the same time Receiving input and sending directions To all their mobiles Their little specialized parts That were moving around And the radioactive muck And so you would get their basic commentary And then all the levels below that Of interaction And I really enjoyed writing about that I thought it was quite exciting When I was doing it But the trouble is that I think I only found one person Who actually understood Without having it explained to them What was going on in that story Almost no one else understood And I felt like that was the case Where my aliens had gotten too alien For their own good You've undertaken another difficult writing task That being world building In your novel The Snow Queen It's a wonderful work of science fantasy You would call it science fantasy Wouldn't you? I suppose so actually It is, you know, in its heart It's a science fiction story But it does have heavy mythological elements Which I think give it a fantasy-like quality And I wasn't fighting that at all I was striving for a sort of fusion Oh good, well then I can call it A wonderful work of science fantasy It's got a very involved plot And a very exciting narrative This must have taken a tremendous amount Of background development Yes, probably Oh gosh That book was quite an incredible thing For me to write that book Because I wound up being It was over 600 pages of manuscript It's almost 200,000 words long And when I started writing it I had never written a complete novel All at once With Outcast of Heaven Belt I had written a novella And then I had increased in size To that of a novel And I was feeling kind of daunted About the very idea of writing a normal What I thought would be a normal length novel Of about 200 pages But I finally did sit down And start to write it And the more I wrote The more I realized That it was not going to stop at 200 pages I think I had gotten through 100 pages And realized that I had barely gotten Into the plot at all My writing And from then on I could only just go on And write and write and write And see where it led me It got more and more complicated As it went along Until I really despaired at times That I would never be able To finish the thing It was a great comfort to me When I finally sat down And figured out How everything had to fit together To get to the end of the book I did a fair amount of background work Beforehand But actually I wound up doing A great deal of the work I think during the process Of writing the book I had conceived of the idea Of the wicked city of Carbuckle Which gets its name Because it's either a jewel Or a fester Depending on your point of view But I wanted it to be Sort of a place Where all kinds of cultures From all kinds of worlds Came together And mixed and mingled And in trying to make A portrait of the city I needed a lot of Different characters With a lot of different Backgrounds behind them And so I would Whenever I needed A new character I would write one Into the story And then I'd kind of have To figure out Where they came from Frequently I don't Lay everything out Before I actually Start to write a book I have kind of A basic structure Which I think It was being sort of Like a trellis And then the story Is a line That grows up Through it And fills it in And fleshes it out And things And I think Because I didn't have Any idea of How big the snow queen Was going to be It got even more Complex You know In the process Than most of the things Most of the things I have a clearer idea Ahead of time Of what they're going To be about But it was just so massive It was impossible To think about Everything ahead of time It was mostly The scientific research I think that I did Ahead of time Reading up on black holes And things like that I regret that black holes And clones Became such kind of Stereotypes During the time Which I was reading The book They weren't They were not Quite such archetypal Sci-fi cliches When I started Writing the book As they are now But at least Since I hope The book will appeal To a wide audience At least Maybe people Who don't even Regularly read Science fiction Will know What I'm talking about And I talk about Black holes and clones At this point But I did I did do a fair amount Of technical reading Or semi-technical reading On the nature Of black holes And using them As means of travel In order to Set up the Basic science fictional Premises of the book And I did I happened to read Robert Graves' book The White Goddess Just before I Started writing The Snow Queen And that I found that Influenced me heavily And that I got A lot of Of the mythical Fantasy type elements Out of that And kind of Wove them into The texture Of the book And I tried To create Societies Which would Kind of Fit in with The most Technical and Non-technical Societies Which would Fit comfortably With kind of The underlying Themes and Premises of the book And from there I just Things just Growed Like Tomsy I guess One of the Characters Comes from A very Advanced Society The most Technologically Dominant Society In the book Started out As a Walk-on Character His name Is Gandolino And he Came along With one Of the major Characters In the book And he Just started Acting up And out Of his Personality I kind Of saw A whole Cultural Stereotype Growing And I Realized Part of Actually Part of Where he Came from Was that I had Been reading A lot Of books About I've been Reading Some fiction Books About Romans In Britain Because I've Always been Fascinated By Romans In Britain Part of The Archaeology Thing I guess And Just the Kind of Fascination With The Science Fictional Reversal Where The Highly Cultured People Are The People Who Too Often Wind Up In Sword And Sorcery Fantasies The Kind Of Dark And Swarthy People And They're Usually Spelping Around In The Bushes But They Were The People Who Were Suave And Sophisticated And On Top And The People With Red Hair And Freckles And Green Eyes Were Running Running Running Around Like Howling Barbarians In The Brush And I Thought That Was A Delightful Twist Thinking About Cultural Arrogance And How The Romans Sort Of Resembled Victorian English In That Way I Just Got Into A Mindset To Write About That Sort Of Character I Think And So Without Even Realizing It This Particular Character Just Began Taking On All These Aspects And Out Of Him I Realized What His Whole Culture Must Be Like And It Became One Of The Important Societies In The Book And Just Odd Little Things Happened Like That That The Book Kind Of Grew Up In A Strange Way It Was Quite An Indescribable Thing And If I Had Known Ahead Of Time What I Was Getting Into I Would Never Have Started It Probably Just As Well That We Can't See The Future I Think Oh Yes Correct Me If I'm Wrong But Didn't I Read Somewhere That Your Story Is Based Upon The Hans Christian Anderson Fairy Tale Called The Snow Queen Oh Yes It Is As Matter Of Fact That Was My Original Inspiration For The Book There Is A Cartoon An Animated Movie Of The Snow If You Can Wait Through 15 Minutes Of Art Linkletter Talking To Children At The Beginning Of It It It's Really Quite Well Done I Was Interested In It You Know I First Seen That Movie When I Was In About Eighth Grade And Oh This Is Silly But When I Saw It Again Back During The Seventies Sometime I I Realized What An Interesting Fairy Tale It Is It's Particular Amount About Near Eastern And European Mythology You See A Lot Of Symbolic Archetypes You See Ravens And Stags And The Wicked Stepmother And The Sweet Young Innocent And Things Like That Which You Know They All Actually Have Their Archetypes Back In European And Near Eastern Mythology And That Well That Just As An Aside That Was Why The Robert Graves Book On The White Goddess And On All That Mythology In Europe And The New East Fit In So Perfectly With This Particular Story That Hans Christian Anderson Had Written Down But Was Essentially One Of These Old Tales Which Are Kind Of Twisted Up Mythology And The Thing That Interested Me Especially About This Particular Tale Was That There Is No Prince In It It It Usually Prince Who And Exciting Things Like Fighting The Dragons And Things Like That And Waking Up The Sleeping Maiden And The Women In The Story Are Usually Either The Wicked Old Witch Or Some Helpless Simpering Creature And You know I get Sort of Bored With That Kind Of Thing But I Was Very Interested This Book Was Quite A Twist Because Or This Fairy Tale Was Quite A Twist Because All The Main Roles In It Were Played By Women The Basic Idea Of The Story Is That There Are A Little Girl And A Little Boy Who Are Friends And The Little Boy Is Stolen Away By The Snow Queen Who Is Kind Of And Unique And I Was In The Mood To Do A Story In Which Women Played Major Roles In The Book And So I Thought That Was A Good Jumping Off Point For It And So I You Know From There Everything Else Just Started Growing Basically I Read Robert Graves Book And I Said Boy This Gives Me A Lot More Fuel For The Fire And I Just Started Writing At That Point I Didn't Want To Write A Fantasy Though I Didn't Want To Just Make It A Retelling Of The Fairy Tale Basically I Really Wanted It To Be A Whole New Story And I Wanted It To To Be Science Fiction As Well Because That's Just The Way My Brain Works I Guess I Have Written A Couple Of Fantasy Stories Recently I I Always Enjoyed Reading Fantasy Author Critic And Editor Ben Bova Has Praised Joan Vingy For Blending Believable Science With Believable Characters No Easy Task The Best Way To Know And Appreciate Joan Vingy Is To Buy One Of Her Books And Start Reading For Those Who Do There Should Be No Disappointments This Is David Cruz And David Carson This Has Been The Science Fiction Radio Show A Presentation Of The Permian Basin Science Fiction Association In Conjunction With KOCV FM And Odessa College Odessa Texas

segments.text: A commentary on science fiction today
Presented by the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association
This show will be an interview with science fiction author Joan D. Vingy
Joan Vingy is one of the best of the group of young science fiction authors that appeared in the 70s
Her first story, Tin Soldier, was published in 1974
And since then she's written two novels and a number of novellas and short stories
In 1977 she received a Hugo Award for one of her stories, Eyes of Amber
She has experimented convincingly with a future history and with world building
And is noted for her credible and fascinating aliens
Perhaps most readers though respond most strongly to her characters
They are vividly and realistically drawn, easily identified with
And they remain with the reader long after he's finished one of her stories
How did you get started writing science fiction?
Well, there are sort of two versions of that in a way
Which began after I first got married to Werner Vingy, my now ex-husband
He was a science fiction writer at the time
And I had been a person who fooled around with writing for a while before that
I would just diddle around with it
I used to want to be an artist and writing was just something I did kind of privately
And never showed to anybody and rarely finished anything either
But Werner encouraged me to take it seriously if I was going to write
By that time I'd abandoned wanting to be an artist
Because my college art professors had ruined my desire to do art
And I was sort of casting about
And he knew that I liked to write
And so he encouraged me to attempt to take it seriously
And sit down and do something and finish it
And so I decided that I would take him up on that
And I started doing a story
Which turned out to be the first story that I sold
And when I started writing it
I didn't know if I'd ever get it finished or anything
But I did get it finished
And I showed it to him
And he said he thought it was saleable
And so I started sending it out
And after that I was hooked of course
And I wanted to go on being a writer
Does your background in anthropology have much influence on your writing?
Well actually it does play a pretty big role in the writing
Because I find that anthropology and science fiction
Have a lot of things in common for me
And archaeology is the anthropology of the past
And science fiction for me is the anthropology of the future
They form sort of a long continuum
And the thing I like about both science fiction and anthropology
Is that they allow you to see how other people do things
And that other people's lives are not led the same way yours is
And that there are other ways of coping
That aren't necessarily the ones you've always known
That other people do things differently
And get along perfectly well that way
I love the way that both anthropology and science fiction
Can take your preconceptions and kind of turn them around 180 degrees
And make you say gee I never thought of it like that before
Specifically I like to use my anthropological background too
When I'm setting up societies for the stories that I'm going to write
I do sort of an ethnography which is a cultural study
Only I have to make up details of the culture in general
Instead of just studying an anthropological culture
I do get a lot of details, bits and pieces of interesting societies
Which I recombine sometimes to create science fictional societies
It gives you a way of thinking
I think that's very useful when you're writing a science fiction story
Hoping that when you send your rocket ship out into the galaxy
It's not going to come to a planet where everyone acts like 1950s Earth
And I really enjoy exploring differences in societies
And well mythology is kind of an offshoot of anthropology
That I find is very useful to science fiction too
I get a lot of story ideas from mythology
And a lot of, I think, just kind of underlying strengths
And I like to weave them into the science fiction
Which is what I most like to write
And I think it gives a stronger appeal somehow
Could that be because we have sort of a common background of folktales and myths
And by weaving these into your stories
You sort of reinforce or update some of the old basic stories
That our culture is based on
Right, yeah, I think very much so
I think there really are certain universalities in myths too
At a very deep and basic level
And if you could capture some of that same feeling
In a story when you write it
Maybe by employing elements consciously or unconsciously
Of, you know, out of the mythology
I think that you could really have a very deep emotional impact on the reader
Which I think is probably what every writer would like to do
I've noticed that a lot of your stories seem to have a happy ending
Could that be because some of them have their basis in folktales
Or is it because you're just basically an optimistic person?
I think it's more that I'm basically an optimistic person
Actually, not every single one of my stories is based on a folktale
A lot of them do have those elements in them
It's just that I really, I hate to leave a story feeling totally depressed by it
And so I think I hate to write a story that's totally depressing
Frequently, I think the stories have sort of bittersweet endings
Or, you know, people don't walk off hand in hand into the sunset
They're usually dragging along, you know, a few suitcases full of problems too
But, you know, I think the way life is, it's unrealistic usually to write a totally happy ending
But I do like to have an optimistic ending
When I read things, I relate to them on a very personal level
I get very involved in a story
And if it's a story, the end result of which is to make me feel totally depressed
And feel like, you know, why bother to live?
I really don't like being left feeling that way
And I think I don't like feeling that way when I write, too
Yes, it seems that you get very involved with your characters that you create
Is it because you flesh them out so well when you create them?
Or is it because the characters are sort of variations on yourself?
Well, I think probably some of both
I think a lot of my favorite characters are, you know, bits and pieces of me
I don't know that any one of them is all me
I think all people have different aspects of their personality
Which come to the fore at different times
And I think when you're writing, you can't help but
I really do like characters in stories
I like to read about characters who seem real
And so I like to try and make my own characters as real as possible when I write them
And I think, you know, by getting inside their heads
I invariably, you know, stick a few of my thoughts in there
I do have some characters who are based on other people I know
I like to, you know, well, when I write about strange things
And new ideas in different societies
I like to put people who are recognizably human
Even if they're aliens, I suppose
But people that the reader can relate to into those situations
And let the reader see how the human being reacts
To the strange set of circumstances
It's not simply the strange set of circumstances which interests me
Although that's, I think, why I write science fiction
I don't like to write about the same old day-to-day thing
I like to explore new ground
But I like to do it with actual characters
Who, you know, come as close as possible
I like to see what they do in the given circumstances
Science fiction is the only literature
Which allows you to explore the future
Which opens up quite a few vistas
That mainstream literature just doesn't have
And that's really what I like about science fiction
I read my first science fiction book
When I was in ninth grade
And I just felt like, you know
Boy, where has this been all my life
I was just swept away by it
And I felt like I really hardly wanted to read anything
It was just so exciting to me
To know these new worlds opened up to me
Yes, I remember one of the characters in Eyes of Amber
And it seems like music plays an important role in your writing
I seem to relate to music on a kind of subliminal level
I guess it operates something like mythology for me
I frequently get down into the song
And start wondering what's going on in the background of it
And, you know, the situation that's set up in the song
Leads me to think, well, who are the people involved in this
And how did they get here
And what is this talking about?
Actually, I tend to relate to songs in a very personal way
That they have a kind of reality about them
I frequently can't help thinking that the songwriter
Must have written that about his or her own experience
Even though I know it's no more likely that they did
And that someone writing fiction necessarily wrote a story about their own life
But I just enjoy music tremendously
And it really stimulates creative juices for me
So I frequently do wind up being inspired to write certain things
The title of that story is taken from the song by Buffy St. Marie
Which is about someone who has a demon lover
And sort of fit into the context of the story
Where the alien woman thinks of the space probe as a demon
Because it does respond to her
Although she doesn't know it's the human beings on Earth
She relates to it as another being
And has this kind of fascination for it
And it's just taking little elements like that
It's one of the pleasures of writing for me
Since you do have a rather good background in anthropology
How do you go about constructing your aliens?
Oh, that's an interesting question, actually
I don't think I have any particular method for constructing aliens
They frequently kind of arise out of other givens in the situation
In Eyes of Amber, the aliens, although they seem superficially humanoid
Were actually constructed for an entirely different nitrogen-breathing situation
And they had a different situation on a world
And one of the, yes, one of the noons of Saturn
A world which was extremely cold
Which meant that they spent part of the time in the sky
Part on the land and part in the water
And the creatures in Crystal Ship were sort of marsupial-like
And the creatures in my story, to Belle the cat
They just lived on pure radiation
They lived in essentially a hot, you know, an incredibly radioactively hot swamp on a planet
But there's actually no real pattern to any of them
The creatures living in the cave came out of the idea of there being
Essentially natural nuclear reactors forming on the Earth
There was an article somewhere about how there seemed to be the fossil remains of one somewhere in Africa, I think
It seemed that at some point a concentration of ore had gotten so radioactively hot
That it had actually started a thermonuclear reaction
Not a bomb, but just a, you know, kind of a roiling, boiling situation
And so I had these creatures that had come from a whole planet that was like that
And had been shipwrecked essentially on this planet
